This is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI *scope* is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped` gives you a fresh `DbContext` for each request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app has a single root scope for its entire lifetime, so `AddScoped` behaves effectively like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused everywhere — its change tracker accumulates state across navigations.

### Fixes

**Option A — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
You get a new instance every time one is resolved. Simple, but you lose the ability to share a context within a single "unit of work."

**Option B — Create manual scopes (preferred for complex scenarios):**
```csharp
// Register as scoped
builder.Services.AddScoped<MyDbContext>();

// In your ViewModel/page, inject IServiceScopeFactory
public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
{
    using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();
    var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
    // use db — it's disposed when the scope ends
}
```

For most MAUI apps, **`AddTransient`** is the simplest correct answer.
